ding magazines, libel and naturalization law, Scout handbooks, and success manuals, James B. Salazar uncovers how the cultural practices of representing character operated in tandem with the character-building strategies of social reformers. His innovative reading of this archive offers a radical revision of this defining category in U.S. literature and culture, arguing that character was the keystone of a cultural politics of embodiment, a politics that played a critical role in determining-and contesting-the social mobility, political authority, and cultural meaning of the raced and gendered body.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican fictiony19th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aCharacter in literature. 0aCharacterxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aCharacters and characteristics in literature. 0aNational characteristics, American, in literature. 0aPolitical culturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aPolitics and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 0aRhetoricxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistoryy19th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 19th Century.2bisacsh  aBodies.  aStates.  aUnited.  acategory.  acentury.  acharacter.  acharting.  aconcept.  aculture.  acultures.  adevelopment.  aearly-twentieth.  afictional.  afrom.  agenres.  aliterature.  amid-nineteenth.  amovements.  anineteenth-century.  apivotal.  apolitical.  areconceives.  areform.  asocial.  athis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z97831107064440 cprintz978081474130640uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9780814741306.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814786536423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780814786536/original  a9